Headless-nvim integration test suite exercising the real `nvim/lua/steno-ts/init.lua` plugin against actual Neovim buffer/cursor/snippet behavior — a layer the Rust pipeline tests can't reach because they don't invoke `vim.snippet.expand` or real cursor arithmetic. Tests spawn `nvim --headless -u NONE -l <script>` with `nvim/` prepended to `runtimepath` so `require("steno-ts")` resolves to the checked-in plugin file rather than a copy; each script writes a temp JSON snippets fixture, calls `M.setup`, then drives `M._try_expand()`/`M._token_before_cursor` directly.

Every test calls `nvim_missing()` first and returns (not fails) if `nvim` isn't on `PATH` — this is intentional since CI doesn't install nvim; don't turn these into hard failures without also fixing CI. `run_lua(lua: &str) -> Result<Output, String>` writes the script to a uniquely-named temp file (PID + atomic counter to avoid collisions across parallel test runs) and always deletes it afterward, even on failure to spawn. `assert_lua_ok` treats nonzero exit as failure and surfaces stdout/stderr in the error message — Lua `assert()` failures inside the script surface this way.

The two test bodies encode specific regression scenarios and rely on undocumented cross-file contracts:

- `terminal_snippet_keeps_blank_exit_line`: verifies a snippet body `"if(${1}) {\n${0}\\}"` expands to three buffer lines including a blank line for `${0}`, not collapsing it — a real `vim.snippet.expand` quirk not reproducible in the Rust pipeline.
- `extending_a_chord_does_not_eat_preceding_text`: encodes the fixed `build_snippets` contract that *only terminal* strokes get sentinel-wrapped (`@@STROKE@@`) in the snippet dictionary — non-terminal partials of a multi-stroke chord have no dictionary entry and are typed as plain literal text, untouched by the plugin. The test's `plover_type` helper mimics Plover's actual correction model (backspace exactly what Plover itself last typed, then insert), and the assertion checks that text present *before* the chord started survives once the chord is extended and corrected. If `build_snippets` (elsewhere in the crate) ever starts sentinel-wrapping non-terminal partials, this test's premise breaks silently rather than loudly — the coupling is behavioral, not a compile-time one.

`lua_quote` escapes backslashes and quotes to produce a valid double-quoted Lua string literal for embedding filesystem paths into generated scripts; needed because `repo_root()` paths may contain backslashes on some platforms.